{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8b23e882-3445-4089-ae3c-f2f6c623867a","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your .NET crash dump! None of my specialized skills cover dump **analysis** (only collection), but here are the recommended approaches:\n\n**On Linux** — use `dotnet-dump analyze`:\n```bash\n# Install if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Analyze the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-app.dmp\n```\n\nUseful SOS commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary |\n| `dso` (DumpStackObjects) | Objects on the stack |\n\n**On Windows** — use **WinDbg** or **Visual Studio** (File → Open → Dump File).\n\n**Quick triage workflow:**\n1. Run `pe` to check for an unhandled exception\n2. Run `clrthreads` to find faulting thread\n3. Run `setthread <id>` then `clrstack` to see the call stack\n4. Run `dso` to inspect objects near the crash\n\nIf you'd like, upload or copy the `.dmp` file into this directory and I can run `dotnet-dump analyze` interactively to help investigate.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"849f6283-b4f2-43cf-943d-4f777beda02a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET app and wants to analyze it. Let me think about what tools and approaches are available.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see:\n- `dump-collect` - but this is for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them. The description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\"\n\nSo none of the available skills are designed for dump analysis. Let me provide guidance on how to analyze a .NET crash dump.\n\nI should help the user directly with advice on analyzing the dump. The key tools for .NET dump analysis are:\n\n\n- `dotnet-dump analyze` for managed .NET analysis\n- `lldb` with SOS plugin on Linux\n- WinDbg with SOS on Windows\n\nSince we're likely on Linux, I could potentially help with `dotnet-dump analyze` if the user provides the dump file, but this is really interactive work that requires the actual dump. I'll focus on giving them practical guidance instead.","outputTokens":616,"requestId":"A0C1:389D7E:9AF949:BDF571:6A0137F3"},"id":"467735fc-3733-4022-8de6-5c15dc794ad5","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:59:31.365Z","parentId":"6fc74168-dac5-49aa-8cb8-be81c3d1badd"}
